Name: count, dtype: int64

Upon analyzing the class distribution of "is_fraud" column (target variable), we can see that the there is class imbalance.

Most of the transactions are not fraud. If use this data to train our predictive model, the model will be biased towards non-fraudulant cases since it will "assume" that most transactions are not fraud. But we don't want our model to assume, we want our model to detect patterns that give signs of fraud!

So, it is a must that we manage this class imbalance.

In [14]:

In addition to this some of the columns that are not needed for predictions are:

  • cc_num (credit card number)
  • merchant
  • first (first name)
  • last (last name)
  • street
  • zip
  • lat (latitude)
  • long (longitude)
  • job
  • trans_num
  • unix_time
  • merch_lat
  • merch_log

These columns can be dropped safely as well.

4.4. Data Binning¶

Data binning, or bucketing, is a process used to minimize the effects of observation errors. It is the process of transforming numerical variables into their categorical counterparts.

In other words, binning will take a column with continuous numbers and place the numbers in “bins” based on ranges that we determine. This will give us a new categorical variable feature.

In [34]:
bins = [0, 18, 25, 35, 45, 55, 65, 75, 85, 100]  # cut points
labels = ["0-18", "18-25", "26-35", "36-45", "46-55", 
          "56-65", "66-75", "76-85", "86-96"] # bin labels

# Create a new column 'age_group' on training set that indicates the bin each age falls into
X_train["age_group"] = pd.cut(
    X_train["age"], 
    bins=bins, 
    labels=labels, 
    right=True,   # include the right edge (e.g., 25 goes into "18-25")
    include_lowest=True
)

# Drop the age column on training set
X_train.drop(columns=['age'], inplace = True)

# Create a new column 'age_group' on test set that indicates the bin each age falls into
X_test["age_group"] = pd.cut(
    X_test["age"], 
    bins=bins, 
    labels=labels, 
    right=True,   # include the right edge (e.g., 25 goes into "18-25")
    include_lowest=True
)

# Drop the age column on test set
X_test.drop(columns=['age'], inplace = True)
In [35]:
# Define amount labels for quartile binning
amount_labels = ["Q1_Low", "Q2_Medium_Low", "Q3_Medium_High", "Q4_High"]

# Create a new column 'amount_group' on training set that indicates the bin each amount falls into
X_train["amount_group"] = pd.cut(
    X_train["amt"], 
    bins=4, 
    labels=amount_labels
)

# Drop the amount column on training set
# X_train.drop(columns=['amt'], inplace = True)

# Create a new column 'amount_group' on test set that indicates the bin each amount falls into
X_test["amount_group"] = pd.cut(
    X_test["amt"], 
    bins=4, 
    labels=amount_labels
)

# Drop the age column on test set
# X_test.drop(columns=['amt'], inplace = True)

After binning amount, I did not drop the amount coulmn beacuse dropping the column had a significant impact on the recall of the postive class (1/Fraud) which I found out after training the model only using the binned column 'amount_group'. It Dropped from 0.88 to 0.75. So, I will be using the 'amt' feature for trannning.

4.5. Encoding Categorical Columns¶

In [40]:
categorical_columns = ['category', 'gender', 'city', 'state', 'age_group', 'trans_day_name', 'amount_group']

# Encode categorical columns
for column in categorical_columns:
    # Initilize label encoder
    label_encoder = LabelEncoder()
            
    # Fit encoder on training data
    label_encoder.fit(X_train[column])
    
    # Transform both the training and test data
    X_train[column] = label_encoder.transform(X_train[column])
    X_test[column] = label_encoder.transform(X_test[column])

# Sets the current active experiment to the "Credit_Card_Fraud_Detection" experiment and returns the Experiment metadata
lightgbm_experiment = mlflow.set_experiment("Credit_Card_Fraud_Detection")

# Define a run name for this iteration of training.
# If this is not set, a unique name will be auto-generated for your run.
run_name = "lightgbm_random_search"

# Define an artifact path that the model will be saved to.
artifact_path = "lightbgm_random_search"
In [61]:
# Create the random grid of the model hyperparameters
rs_params = {
        'max_depth': (10, 13),
        'num_leaves': (200, 550),
        'n_estimators': (100, 150)
}

# Use the random grid to search for best hyperparameters
# First create the base model to tune
LightGBM_classifier = LGBMClassifier(random_state = 42, device = 'cuda')

# Random search of parameters, using 3 fold cross validation, 
# search across 100 different combinations, and use all available cores
LightGBM_random = RandomizedSearchCV(estimator = LightGBM_classifier, 
                                     param_distributions = rs_params,
                                     n_iter = 10, scoring='recall', 
                                     cv = 3, verbose = 1, n_jobs=-1)


# Fit the random search model
LightGBM_random.fit(X_train_resampled, y_train_resampled);

# Initiate the MLflow run context
with mlflow.start_run(run_name=run_name) as run:

    # Log the BEST parameters found by RandomizedSearchCV
    mlflow.log_params(LightGBM_random.best_params_)

    # Log the error metrics
    mlflow.log_metrics(metrics)

    # Log an instance of the trained model for later use

It took more than an hour to calculate the SHAP values eventhough I used GPU for calculation and it did not even complete due to error.¶

Upon research, I found out that the error was likely due to a minor numerical discrepancy between the GPU model prediction and the GPUTree explanation.

So, I will be using 100k samples from the training set (SMOTE applied) to calculate the SHAP values.¶
